2:1 Therefore, first of all I urge that requests, prayers, intercessions, and thanksgiving be made on behalf of all people— 
2:2 for kings and all who are in authority—so we may live a peaceful and quiet life in all godliness and respectfulness. 
2:3 This is good and pleasing in the sight of God our Savior. 
2:4 He desires all men to be saved and come into the knowledge of the truth. 
2:5 , 
2:6 who gave Himself as a ransom for all—the testimony at the proper time. 
2:7 For this I was appointed a herald and an emissary (I am telling the truth; I am not lying), a teacher of the Gentiles in faithfulness and truth. 
2:8 So I desire all men to pray everywhere, lifting up holy hands, without anger and argument. 
2:9 Likewise, women are to adorn themselves in appropriate clothing with modesty and sound judgment—not in seductive hairstyles and gold or pearls or costly clothing, 
2:10 but what is suitable for women claiming godliness, through good deeds. 
2:11 Let a woman receive training in a quiet demeanor with complete respect for order. 
2:12 But I do not allow a woman to train or dictate to a man, but to be in a quiet demeanor. 
2:13 For Adam was formed first, then Eve. 
2:14 Also Adam was not deceived but the woman—being deceived, she fell into transgression. 
2:15 Nevertheless, she will be sustained through childbearing—if they continue in faithfulness and love and holiness, with sound judgment. 
3:1 Trustworthy is the saying: “If any man aspires to the office of overseer, he desires a good work.” 
3:2 An overseer, then, must be beyond criticism—the husband of one wife, clear-minded, self-controlled, respectable, hospitable, able to teach, 
3:3 not addicted to wine, not violent but gentle, peaceable, free from the love of money, 
3:4 managing his own household well, keeping his children under control with all respectfulness. 
3:5 (But if someone does not know how to manage his own household, how will he care for God’s community?) 
3:6 He must not be a new believer, or he may become puffed up and fall into the same judgment as the devil. 
3:7 Furthermore, he must have a good reputation with those outside, so that he will not fall into disgrace and the devil’s trap. 
3:8 Servant-leaders likewise must be dignified, not double-speaking, not addicted to much wine, not greedy for dishonest gain. 
3:9 They must keep hold of the mystery of the faith with a clear conscience. 
3:10 Also let them first be tested—then let those who are blameless serve as servant-leaders. 
3:11 Women likewise must be dignified, not backbiting; clear-minded, trustworthy in every respect. 
3:12 Let servant-leaders be husbands of one wife, managing their children and their own households well. 
3:13 . 
3:14 These things I write to you, hoping to come to you shortly. 
3:15 But if I delay, I write so you may know how one ought to conduct himself in the household of God—which is the community of the living God, a pillar and foundation of truth. 
3:16 Now beyond question, great is the mystery of godliness: He was revealed in the flesh, Vindicated in the Spirit, Seen by angels, Proclaimed among the nations, Trusted throughout the world, Taken up in glory. 
